<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/228080-yeahhh-when-the-synopsis-states-that">Yeahhh... when the synopsis states that sage is &quot;actually a boy&quot;, does that mean she&#39;s a trans woman? Because immediately that sort of misgendering bullshit puts me off.</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_228080'><a id="like_count_community_question_228080" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/228080?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">21 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F5982474-almost-perfect">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/228080-yeahhh-when-the-synopsis-states-that">6 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/228080-yeahhh-when-the-synopsis-states-that">See all 6 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/1262993-brian"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1442484559i/1262993._UX100_CR0,25,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/1262993-brian">Brian</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Sage is a transwoman. I didn&apos;t write the synopsis, and newer versions of the book say she is &apos;biologically male.&apos; Actually, I think the book is better<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Sage is a transwoman. I didn't write the synopsis, and newer versions of the book say she is 'biologically male.' Actually, I think the book is better if you learn to like Sage as a person first, rather than a gender. I recommend people read ALMOST PERFECT without reading the synopsis. Thanks for your question.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
