<div id="review_95172928" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/95172928" />
    <a title="Colin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51647-colin"><img alt="Colin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408140874p2/51647.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/95172928?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Colin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Colin" href="/user/show/51647-colin">Colin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51647-colin?shelf=genderstudies">genderstudies</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51647-colin?shelf=youngadultlit">youngadultlit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51647-colin?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer95172928" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7366309604536447447">This was a fast read, but it was difficult. Though it was realistic, it was hard to read all about the main character&apos;s process working through his transphobia, and the whole thing reeked of tragi-trans. Also, there were infuriating moments of racism thrown in. I&apos;d say this isn&apos;t a book for trans teens, but may help non-trans people empathize and somewhat better understand some of the dangers and emotional struggles facing mainstream trans people, and may illuminate and hopefully combat some of </span>
  <span id="freeText7366309604536447447" style="display:none">This was a fast read, but it was difficult. Though it was realistic, it was hard to read all about the main character's process working through his transphobia, and the whole thing reeked of tragi-trans. Also, there were infuriating moments of racism thrown in. I'd say this isn't a book for trans teens, but may help non-trans people empathize and somewhat better understand some of the dangers and emotional struggles facing mainstream trans people, and may illuminate and hopefully combat some of their own transphobia.<br /><br />It's hard for me to read YA books about trans folks; they either are filled with stereotypes and/or tragi-trans despair, like <i>Luna</i> or this book, or they go the to the other extreme and seem unrealistically chipper, like <i>Parrotfish</i>. At this point in YA publishing, it's still "taking a risk" (as Katcher says in his acknowledgments) to publish *anything* involving trans characters, so books seem to be admired for being out there at all. But I'm ready for more complexity. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7366309604536447447" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


