  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_704425506" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/704425506" />
    <a title="James" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3741486-james"><img alt="James" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1440506640p2/3741486.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/704425506?book_show_action=true">Aug 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James" href="/user/show/3741486-james">James</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer704425506" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5167444813986745456">I&apos;m usually desperate to read any lgbt book I can get my hands on, and when I found a book with a trans* character I was really excited! By the end of the book however, I was simply angry and disappointed.<br/><br/>Logan (the narrator) is a regular boy in a small town. Sage (the love interest) is a new student at Logan&apos;s school. Logan finds her attractive and wants to date her. Sage likes Logan too but warns him that she&apos;s not what he&apos;s looking for. Logan pursuits her none the less. And when Sage is revea</span>
  <span id="freeText5167444813986745456" style="display:none">I'm usually desperate to read any lgbt book I can get my hands on, and when I found a book with a trans* character I was really excited! By the end of the book however, I was simply angry and disappointed.<br /><br />Logan (the narrator) is a regular boy in a small town. Sage (the love interest) is a new student at Logan's school. Logan finds her attractive and wants to date her. Sage likes Logan too but warns him that she's not what he's looking for. Logan pursuits her none the less. And when Sage is revealed to be mtf Logan reacts poorly to put it lightly.<br /><br />And this is where I start to have a problem with the book. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[While on one hand I understand that Logan behaves and reacts as most boys would (with homophobic and transphobic slurs and insults) I can't help but hate him. Even Sage, our poor abused trans* woman struggling with finding support, is difficult to sympathize with due to her repeated mistakes and lack of self preservation.<br /><br />The worst part of the book for me is that no one seems to learn or grow. By the end of the book Logan is not any more accepting and Sage is no more confident. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />If you're looking for a well written or hopeful trans* novel I would suggest you look else where.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5167444813986745456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


